	<!-- <h2></h2> -->
			<div class="longform post_img fullwidth">
			<img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/2024-working-copy.jpg" alt="" class="entry_post"/>
		</div>
				<h1>Lit Hub’s Most Anticipated Books of 2024</h1>
		<h2>230 Books We’re Looking Forward to Reading This Year</h2>
    <div class="inner">
		<div class="post_header_wrapper">
    				</div>
				<div class="author_info" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
			<div class="author_name">By&nbsp;<a href="https://lithub.com/author/literary-hub/" itemprop="url"><span itemprop="name">Literary&nbsp;Hub</span></a></div>
			<div class="author_hr"><hr/></div>
			<div class="publish_date">January 3, 2024</div>
		</div>
		<div class="social_links">
						<a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=lithub&text=Lit+Hub%E2%80%99s+Most+Anticipated+Books+of+2024&url=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Flit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024%2F"><span class="social_twitter"></span></a>
			<a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Flit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024%2F&t=Lit+Hub%E2%80%99s+Most+Anticipated+Books+of+2024"><span class="social_facebook"></span></a>
					</div>
    <div class="inner">
    	<!-- Begin main content -->
    	<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
    			
										<!-- Begin each blog post -->
						<div class="post_wrapper" style="padding-top:0;">
							<div class="post_inner_wrapper">
						    	<div class="post_wrapper_inner">
										<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
								        
										<p>Happy New Year, readers. 2023 had its <a href="https://lithub.com/the-10-biggest-literary-stories-of-the-year-3/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ups and downs (mostly downs)</a>, but as always, at least it brought us some <a href="https://lithub.com/the-38-best-books-we-read-in-2023/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">very good books</a>. But now that you’ve read <a href="https://lithub.com/the-ultimate-best-books-of-2023-list/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">all the books last year had to offer</a> (right?), it’s time for a brand new list.</p>
<p>Here are the books Literary Hub editors are most looking forward to (so far!) in the months to come.</p>
<h1><strong>JANUARY</strong></h1>
<p><img decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" data-attachment-id="231316" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/81njrvajx6l-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81NJrVaJX6L._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Vanessa Chan, The Storm We Made" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81NJrVaJX6L._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81NJrVaJX6L._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231316" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81NJrVaJX6L._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" alt="Vanessa Chan, The Storm We Made " width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81NJrVaJX6L._SL1500_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81NJrVaJX6L._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81NJrVaJX6L._SL1500_-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81NJrVaJX6L._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81NJrVaJX6L._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81NJrVaJX6L._SL1500_.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Vanessa Chan, </strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668015148" class="external" target="_blank"><strong><em>The Storm We Made</em></strong></a><br />
<strong>S&amp;S/Marysue Rucci Books, January 2</strong></h5>
<p>This highly anticipated debut novel from Vanessa Chan tells the story of a housewife turned spy in occupied Malaya during WWII. The chapters alternate between Cecily’s perspective and those of her children: her teenage son, one of many who’s gone missing; her daughter Jujube, who spends her days catering to Japanese soldiers; and her youngest daughter, Jasmin, hidden away for her own safety. An epic historical novel that’s both propulsive and poignant—expect to see this one about town. <em>–Eliza Smith, special projects editor</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231317" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71f3aryifxl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71F3ArYIfXL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="994,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Tara Isabella Burton, Here in Avalon" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71F3ArYIfXL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71F3ArYIfXL._SL1500_-679x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231317" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71F3ArYIfXL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" alt="Tara Isabella Burton, Here in Avalon " width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71F3ArYIfXL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71F3ArYIfXL._SL1500_-679x1024.jpg 679w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71F3ArYIfXL._SL1500_-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71F3ArYIfXL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71F3ArYIfXL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71F3ArYIfXL._SL1500_.jpg 994w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Tara Isabella Burton, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781982170097" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Here in Avalon</em></a><br />
Simon &amp; Schuster, January 2</strong></h5>
<p>Tara Isabella Burton is a fascinating thinker and writer—she has a doctorate in theology from Oxford, and in addition to novels she writes nonfiction on things like contemporary American post-religious spirituality and our obsession with self-branding. I particularly loved her 2018 novel <em>Social Creature </em>(think Tom Ripley gets Instagram), so would I like to read her new book about a possibly magical theater cult? I would, I would. <em>–Emily Temple, managing editor</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231318" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/911hbvfegl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/911HBvfEGL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Mike McCormack, This Plague of Souls" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/911HBvfEGL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/911HBvfEGL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231318" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/911HBvfEGL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" alt="Mike McCormack, This Plague of Souls " width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/911HBvfEGL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/911HBvfEGL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/911HBvfEGL._SL1500_-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/911HBvfEGL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/911HBvfEGL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/911HBvfEGL._SL1500_.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Mike McCormack, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781641295789" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>This Plague of Souls</em></a><br />
Soho Press, January 2</strong></h5>
<p>I was blown away—or let’s be specific and say both profoundly moved and intellectually thrilled—by Irish writer McCormack’s 2016 <em>Solar Bones</em>, a novel about death (and also, necessarily, life) told in a single, enthralling sentence. Thus it is no surprise I am very much anticipating his next book, an “existential noir” in which a man returns home from prison to find his house empty, his family gone—and calls from a mysterious man who claims he can reveal the truth. <em>–ET</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231319" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/a1qvxanxzol-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1QVXANXzOL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Kate Brody, Rabbit Hole" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1QVXANXzOL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1QVXANXzOL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231319" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1QVXANXzOL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" alt="Kate Brody, Rabbit Hole " width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1QVXANXzOL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1QVXANXzOL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1QVXANXzOL._SL1500_-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1QVXANXzOL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1QVXANXzOL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1QVXANXzOL._SL1500_.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Kate Brody, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781641294874" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Rabbit Hole</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Soho Crime, January 2</strong></h5>
<p>This promising debut looks perfect for our Internet sleuth-y, murder-fixated age. It’s about a woman named Teddy whose sister, Angie, disappeared ten years ago, leaving behind a cold case and a broken family. Now their father has killed himself, and upon going through his belongings, Teddy discovers that he was involved in a Reddit community concentrated on solving Angie’s case. Teddy can’t help herself and falls down the “rabbit hole” of the Reddit community’s obsession, and allows it to take over her life. She forms a friendship with another member of the community, and slowly but surely loses sense of any previous priority, loses sense of who she was before. It’s twisty and addictive, just like the Reddit community, and the reader becomes as obsessed as Teddy is to solve this mystery. –<em>Julia Hass, contributing editor</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231320" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/91gs6qw5xdl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91gs6Qw5XdL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="993,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Alvaro Enrigue, tr. Natasha Wimmer, You Dreamed of Empires" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91gs6Qw5XdL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91gs6Qw5XdL._SL1500_-678x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231320" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91gs6Qw5XdL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" alt="Alvaro Enrigue, tr. Natasha Wimmer, You Dreamed of Empires " width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91gs6Qw5XdL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91gs6Qw5XdL._SL1500_-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91gs6Qw5XdL._SL1500_-768x1160.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91gs6Qw5XdL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91gs6Qw5XdL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91gs6Qw5XdL._SL1500_.jpg 993w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Alvaro Enrigue, trans. Natasha Wimmer, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593544792" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>You Dreamed of Empires</em></a><br />
Riverhead, January 9</strong></h5>
<p>Hell yes. I’m very much looking forward to reading another one of Enrigue’s bonkers, brain-bending historical novels (in his 2016 novel, <em>Sudden Death</em>, also translated by Wimmer, the Italian painter Caravaggio and the Spanish poet Francisco de Quevedo play tennis with a ball made from Anne Boleyn’s hair). Cortés also features heavily in <em>Sudden Death</em>, and Enrigue returns to his story in <em>You Dreamed of Empire</em>—but of course, it will not be the story we know, but a strange, fantastical version, Enrigue-style. Can’t wait. <em>–ET</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231276" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/nonfiction/9781959030317-20231020212845/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9781959030317-20231020212845.jpg" data-orig-size="776,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="nonfiction" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9781959030317-20231020212845-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9781959030317-20231020212845-662x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231276" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9781959030317-20231020212845-194x300.jpg" alt="nonfiction" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9781959030317-20231020212845-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9781959030317-20231020212845-662x1024.jpg 662w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9781959030317-20231020212845-768x1188.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9781959030317-20231020212845-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9781959030317-20231020212845-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9781959030317-20231020212845.jpg 776w" sizes="(max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Julie Myerson, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781959030317" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Nonfiction</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Tin House Books, January 2</strong></h5>
<p>Myerson&#8217;s latest novel is an urgent, edged book about a novelist&#8217;s relationship with her daughter, who has sunk into a dangerous form of drug addiction, and also her own, cold, mother, or rather her memory of her. As a new parent I thought I might not be able to handle this novel, but as it turned out, I couldn&#8217;t stop reading. <em>–ET</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231321" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/81j1n0rkgzl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81j1N0rkGZL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="987,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Olivie Blake, The Atlas Complex" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81j1N0rkGZL._SL1500_-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81j1N0rkGZL._SL1500_-674x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231321" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81j1N0rkGZL._SL1500_-197x300.jpg" alt="Olivie Blake, The Atlas Complex " width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81j1N0rkGZL._SL1500_-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81j1N0rkGZL._SL1500_-674x1024.jpg 674w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81j1N0rkGZL._SL1500_-768x1167.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81j1N0rkGZL._SL1500_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81j1N0rkGZL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81j1N0rkGZL._SL1500_.jpg 987w" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Olivie Blake, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250855138" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Atlas Complex</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Tor Books, January 9 </strong></h5>
<p>Olivie Blake concludes her much-celebrated dark-academia trilogy in suitably devastating fashion. The six Alexandria Society initiates are back together and back in the library, but not for long: their dangerous caretaker Atlas Blake is still working on his world-ending plan. Expect equal parts romantasy and philosophy—Blake writing about the ethics of power is always a fun ride. <em>–Drew Broussard, contributing editor</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231322" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71bxxi6w4el-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71bXXi6W4eL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Claire Oshetsky, Poor Deer" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71bXXi6W4eL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71bXXi6W4eL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231322" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71bXXi6W4eL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" alt="Claire Oshetsky, Poor Deer " width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71bXXi6W4eL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71bXXi6W4eL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71bXXi6W4eL._SL1500_-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71bXXi6W4eL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71bXXi6W4eL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71bXXi6W4eL._SL1500_.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Claire Oshetsky, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063327665" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Poor Deer</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Ecco, January 9</strong></h5>
<p>The latest from PEN/Faulkner nominee Oshetsky is about a young girl trying to come to terms with the death of her friend. But instead of facing the tragedy, she spins happily-ever-after stories for herself—until a strange creature called Poor Deer makes its way into her tales and demands the truth. By turns strange, beautiful, and tragic, Oshetsky’s story of tragedy and redemption is charming and eerie.<em> –DB</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231323" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71yfdhdvc7l-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71YfDhdVC7L._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Elizabeth Flock, The Furies: Women, Vengeance, and Justice" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71YfDhdVC7L._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71YfDhdVC7L._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231323" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71YfDhdVC7L._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" alt="Elizabeth Flock, The Furies: Women, Vengeance, and Justice " width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71YfDhdVC7L._SL1500_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71YfDhdVC7L._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71YfDhdVC7L._SL1500_-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71YfDhdVC7L._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71YfDhdVC7L._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71YfDhdVC7L._SL1500_.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Elizabeth Flock, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063048805" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Furies: Women, Vengeance, and Justice</em></a><br />
Harper Books, January 9</strong></h5>
<p>Journalist Elizabeth Flock looks at justice with a Taddeo-esque approach, telling the stories of three women who killed after a wrong. There is a Southern U.S. woman who killed her rapist; the leader of a northern Indian gang that avenges victims of domestic violence; and a fighter in an all-female militia in Syria, where ISIS is working to dismantle the lives and rights of women.  –<em>JM</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231324" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71mgs3ha5-l-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71mGS3Ha5-L._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="973,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Jami Attenberg, 1000 Words: A Writer&#8217;s Guide to Staying Creative, Focused, and Productive All Year Round" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71mGS3Ha5-L._SL1500_-195x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71mGS3Ha5-L._SL1500_-664x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231324" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71mGS3Ha5-L._SL1500_-195x300.jpg" alt="Jami Attenberg, 1000 Words: A Writer's Guide to Staying Creative, Focused, and Productive All Year Round " width="195" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71mGS3Ha5-L._SL1500_-195x300.jpg 195w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71mGS3Ha5-L._SL1500_-664x1024.jpg 664w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71mGS3Ha5-L._SL1500_-768x1184.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71mGS3Ha5-L._SL1500_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71mGS3Ha5-L._SL1500_-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71mGS3Ha5-L._SL1500_.jpg 973w" sizes="(max-width: 195px) 100vw, 195px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Jami Attenberg, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668023600" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>1000 Words: A Writer&#8217;s Guide to Staying Creative, Focused, and Productive All Year Round</em></a><br />
S&amp;S/Simon Element, January 9</strong></h5>
<p>Devotees of Attenberg’s fiction (<em>All Grown Up, All This Could Be Yours, </em>many others), and her pandemic-sparked newsletter, Craft Talk, have used her 1000-words-a-day-in-summer model to push novel and book projects along, helped by Attenberg’s feel-good approach to the sweaty toil of ~generative~ work. This offshoot of the project stretches the approach to get you through the year and includes tips from other Names like comedian and essayist Josh Gondelman. It will be the new <em>Bird by Bird</em>, you heard it here first. –<em>JM</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231325" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/91phdmylgvl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91PhDMYLGvL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="993,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Jill McCorkle, Old Crimes: Stories" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91PhDMYLGvL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91PhDMYLGvL._SL1500_-678x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231325" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91PhDMYLGvL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" alt="Jill McCorkle, Old Crimes: Stories " width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91PhDMYLGvL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91PhDMYLGvL._SL1500_-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91PhDMYLGvL._SL1500_-768x1160.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91PhDMYLGvL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91PhDMYLGvL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91PhDMYLGvL._SL1500_.jpg 993w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Jill McCorkle, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781616209735" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Old Crimes: Stories</em></a><br />
Algonquin Books, January 9</strong></h5>
<p>Those waiting for more of Jill McCorkle following her most recent novel <em>Hieroglyphics</em> are in for a treat. Her new short story collection is out January 9, and includes a couple who bring a confession booth into their home, initially for fun, and a phone-line service-man (think the <a href="https://prints.nrm.org/detail/281627/rockwell-the-lineman-1948" class="external" target="_blank">Norman Rockwell painting</a>) who feels estranged from his family in the mobile age. Take me there, Jill! –<em>JM</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231326" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/a1w3p8bh0il-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1w3p8Bh0IL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="994,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Hisham Matar, My Friends" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1w3p8Bh0IL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1w3p8Bh0IL._SL1500_-679x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231326" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1w3p8Bh0IL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" alt="Hisham Matar, My Friends " width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1w3p8Bh0IL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1w3p8Bh0IL._SL1500_-679x1024.jpg 679w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1w3p8Bh0IL._SL1500_-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1w3p8Bh0IL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1w3p8Bh0IL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1w3p8Bh0IL._SL1500_.jpg 994w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Hisham Matar, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780812994841" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>My Friends</em></a><br />
Random House, January 9</strong></h5>
<p>American-Libyan Hisham Matar has written an exile novel with the Arab Spring at its center, pushed along by the power of fiction. Khaled’s journey from Libya to the UK begins when he hears a short story read on the radio about a man eaten alive by a cat–it’s the early days of his waking up to understand the Qaddafi regime. He leaves his parents behind and moves to London to study. There, he attends a protest that turns ugly, stranding him outside his country and family. People who loved Matar’s<em> In the Country of Men</em> will be on this one early. –<em>JM</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231327" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71bfffduil-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BFffDuiL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="900,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Linnea Axelsson, trans. Saskia Vogel, Aednan" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BFffDuiL._SL1500_-180x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BFffDuiL._SL1500_-614x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231327" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BFffDuiL._SL1500_-180x300.jpg" alt="Linnea Axelsson, trans. Saskia Vogel, Aednan " width="180" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BFffDuiL._SL1500_-180x300.jpg 180w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BFffDuiL._SL1500_-614x1024.jpg 614w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BFffDuiL._SL1500_-768x1280.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BFffDuiL._SL1500_-36x60.jpg 36w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BFffDuiL._SL1500_-30x50.jpg 30w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BFffDuiL._SL1500_.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 180px) 100vw, 180px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Linnea Axelsson, trans. Saskia Vogel, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593535455" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Aednan</em></a><br />
Knopf, January 9</strong></h5>
<p>This family epic about two Sámi families begins in the 1910s with matriarch Ristin leading a reindeer migration meets with the new border between Sweden and Norway, rupturing family and culture. Fifty years on, Lise is “educated” in a boarding school for indigenous children, and her daughter Sandra later on fights for Sámi land rights. Listen to a sample <a href="https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/711664/aednan-by-linnea-axelsson/" class="external" target="_blank">here</a>. –<em>JM</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231328" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/91yt4c5ubhl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91yT4C5UBhL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1023,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Lea Carpenter, Ilium" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91yT4C5UBhL._SL1500_-205x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91yT4C5UBhL._SL1500_-698x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231328" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91yT4C5UBhL._SL1500_-205x300.jpg" alt="Lea Carpenter, Ilium " width="205" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91yT4C5UBhL._SL1500_-205x300.jpg 205w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91yT4C5UBhL._SL1500_-698x1024.jpg 698w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91yT4C5UBhL._SL1500_-768x1126.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91yT4C5UBhL._SL1500_-41x60.jpg 41w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91yT4C5UBhL._SL1500_-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91yT4C5UBhL._SL1500_.jpg 1023w" sizes="(max-width: 205px) 100vw, 205px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Lea Carpenter, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593536605" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Ilium</em></a><br />
Knopf, January 16</strong></h5>
<p>At last Lea Carpenter is back (after 2018’s <em>Red, White, Blue</em>) with another sideways approach to the international spy novel—in this one, a young woman is swept off her feet by a much older suitor, but after they’re married, he asks her for a “favor”&#8230;never a good thing. <em>–ET</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231329" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71aezkcfjvl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AEZKcFJVL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="978,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Marie-Helene Bertino, Beautyland" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AEZKcFJVL._SL1500_-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AEZKcFJVL._SL1500_-668x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231329" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AEZKcFJVL._SL1500_-196x300.jpg" alt="Marie-Helene Bertino, Beautyland " width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AEZKcFJVL._SL1500_-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AEZKcFJVL._SL1500_-668x1024.jpg 668w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AEZKcFJVL._SL1500_-768x1178.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AEZKcFJVL._SL1500_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AEZKcFJVL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AEZKcFJVL._SL1500_.jpg 978w" sizes="(max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Marie-Helene Bertino, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374109288" class="external" target="_blank">Beautyland</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>FSG, January 16</strong><strong> </strong></h5>
<p>Marie-Helene Bertino’s wry, melancholy, utterly bewitching third novel is the coming-of-age story of a young Philadelphia woman named Adina who also happens to be an alien—born in 1977 to a hardworking Italian-American “Earth mother” but “activated” at age four by her extraterrestrial superiors and tasked with sending dispatches about the nature of humanity back to her home planet (though where that planet is, what life might be like there, or what her true kin even look like, Adina does not know). Deftly blurring the line between reality and metaphor to create a work of exquisite beauty, joyfully off-kilter humor, and aching sorrow, <em>Beautyland</em>, and Adina’s lonesome journey, will fill and then shatter your heart. <em>–Dan Sheehan, Book Marks editor-in-chief</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231330" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/81b1ygmcbol-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81b1YgMCBOL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="984,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Susan Muaddi Darraj, Behind You is the Sea" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81b1YgMCBOL._SL1500_-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81b1YgMCBOL._SL1500_-672x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231330" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81b1YgMCBOL._SL1500_-197x300.jpg" alt="Susan Muaddi Darraj, Behind You is the Sea " width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81b1YgMCBOL._SL1500_-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81b1YgMCBOL._SL1500_-672x1024.jpg 672w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81b1YgMCBOL._SL1500_-768x1171.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81b1YgMCBOL._SL1500_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81b1YgMCBOL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81b1YgMCBOL._SL1500_.jpg 984w" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Susan Muaddi Darraj, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063324237" class="external" target="_blank">Behind You is the Sea</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>HarperVia, January 16</strong></h5>
<p>This debut novel-in-stories from the award-winning author of <em>A Curious Land: Stories from Home</em> and the <em>Farah Rocks </em>children’s book series is a kaleidoscopic portrait of a Palestinian American community in Baltimore, focusing on three immigrant families and their differing experiences of life in the U.S. Muaddi Darraj, a vocal advocate for Palestinian culture who won an American Book Award in 2016, has written a rich, complex, and moving immigrant story with a beautifully-rendered ensemble cast. <em>–DS</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231331" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71afhcwl9l-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AFHCWl9L._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1007,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Manjula Martin, The Last Fire Season: A Personal and Pyronatural History" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AFHCWl9L._SL1500_-201x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AFHCWl9L._SL1500_-687x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231331" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AFHCWl9L._SL1500_-201x300.jpg" alt="Manjula Martin, The Last Fire Season: A Personal and Pyronatural History " width="201" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AFHCWl9L._SL1500_-201x300.jpg 201w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AFHCWl9L._SL1500_-687x1024.jpg 687w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AFHCWl9L._SL1500_-768x1144.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AFHCWl9L._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AFHCWl9L._SL1500_-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71AFHCWl9L._SL1500_.jpg 1007w" sizes="(max-width: 201px) 100vw, 201px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Manjula Martin, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593317150" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Last Fire Season: A Personal and Pyronatural History</em></a><br />
Pantheon, January 16</strong></h5>
<p>If you’ve fantasized about moving back to your childhood home, you know it can never be quite the same. For Manjula Martin, a tree-change to the Sonoma forests is defined by the naked threat of forest fires and climate change: in 2020, she was evacuated as the state burned. A personal history turned examination of fire and ecology, <em>The Last Fire Season</em> is strangely timely amid a balmy winter some have never experienced before. –<em>JM</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231332" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71wwxj2pdgl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71wwxj2PdGL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1007,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Kyle Chayka, Filterworld: How Algorithms Flattened Culture" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71wwxj2PdGL._SL1500_-201x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71wwxj2PdGL._SL1500_-687x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231332" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71wwxj2PdGL._SL1500_-201x300.jpg" alt="Kyle Chayka, Filterworld: How Algorithms Flattened Culture " width="201" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71wwxj2PdGL._SL1500_-201x300.jpg 201w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71wwxj2PdGL._SL1500_-687x1024.jpg 687w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71wwxj2PdGL._SL1500_-768x1144.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71wwxj2PdGL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71wwxj2PdGL._SL1500_-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71wwxj2PdGL._SL1500_.jpg 1007w" sizes="(max-width: 201px) 100vw, 201px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Kyle Chayka, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780385548281" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Filterworld: How Algorithms Flattened Culture</em></a><br />
Doubleday, January 16</strong></h5>
<p>Kyle Chayka is a master at capturing truths about our online existence (like <a href="https://www.newyorker.com/culture/infinite-scroll/why-the-internet-isnt-fun-anymore" class="external" target="_blank">why the internet isn’t fun anymore</a>) in a manner as astute as it is entertaining. His sophomore book “traces the creeping, machine-guided curation” of the all-powerful algorithm “as it infiltrates the furthest reaches of our digital, physical, and psychological spaces.” I’m as terrified as I am excited to read this one. <em>–Jessie Gaynor, senior editor</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="219989" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/see-the-cover-for-kaveh-akbars-novel-martyr/attachment/9780593537619/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/9780593537619-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1718,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="martyr kaveh akbar" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/9780593537619-201x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/9780593537619-687x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-219989" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/9780593537619-201x300.jpg" alt="martyr kaveh akbar" width="201" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/9780593537619-201x300.jpg 201w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/9780593537619-687x1024.jpg 687w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/9780593537619-768x1144.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/9780593537619-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/9780593537619-1031x1536.jpg 1031w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/9780593537619-1375x2048.jpg 1375w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/9780593537619-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/9780593537619-scaled.jpg 1718w" sizes="(max-width: 201px) 100vw, 201px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Kaveh Akbar, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593537619" class="external" target="_blank">Martyr!</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Knopf, January 23</strong><strong> </strong></h5>
<p>This satirical autobiographical debut novel by Iranian-American writer and Poetry Editor of <em>The Nation </em>is the story of a<strong> </strong>newly sober, martyr-obsessed orphaned son of Iranian immigrants who embarks on a quest to uncover for a long-buried family secret that leads him to a terminally ill painter living out her final days in the Brooklyn Museum. The buzz around <em>Martyr </em>has been intense, and if it’s even a fraction as good as the wildly effusive blurbs suggest (“An absolute jewel of a novel. A diamond. I haven’t loved a book this much in years,” said Tommy Orange, while Lauren Groff called it “The best novel you’ll ever read about the joy of language, addiction, displacement, martyrdom, belonging, homesickness.”), it promises to be one of the most dazzling debuts of the year. <em>–DS</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231333" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/519wr6m0gyl-_sl1000_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519wr6M0GYL._SL1000_.jpg" data-orig-size="663,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Lee Gutkind, The Fine Art of Literary Fist-Fighting" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519wr6M0GYL._SL1000_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519wr6M0GYL._SL1000_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231333" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519wr6M0GYL._SL1000_-199x300.jpg" alt="Lee Gutkind, The Fine Art of Literary Fist-Fighting" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519wr6M0GYL._SL1000_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519wr6M0GYL._SL1000_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519wr6M0GYL._SL1000_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519wr6M0GYL._SL1000_.jpg 663w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Lee Gutkind, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780300251159" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Fine Art of Literary Fist-Fighting: How a Bunch of Rabble-Rousers, Outsiders, and Ne’er-do-wells Concocted Creative Nonfiction</em></a><br />
Yale University Press, January 23</strong></h5>
<p>Though I am sure there were plenty of people who knew how to be weird while telling true stories prior, Lee Gutkind is credited with “fathering” the CNF movement in the ‘60s. Here, he traces his own route from <em>Easy Rider</em> bikie to academic and writer, and looks at how writers like Joan Didion, Uptown Sinclair, Janet Malcolm and James Baldwin navigated the gap between facts and storytelling. –<em>JM</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231334" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/917s2yf99kl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/917s2yf99kL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="992,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Christina Cooke, Broughtupsy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/917s2yf99kL._SL1500_-198x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/917s2yf99kL._SL1500_-677x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231334" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/917s2yf99kL._SL1500_-198x300.jpg" alt="Christina Cooke, Broughtupsy " width="198" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/917s2yf99kL._SL1500_-198x300.jpg 198w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/917s2yf99kL._SL1500_-677x1024.jpg 677w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/917s2yf99kL._SL1500_-768x1161.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/917s2yf99kL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/917s2yf99kL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/917s2yf99kL._SL1500_.jpg 992w" sizes="(max-width: 198px) 100vw, 198px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Christina Cooke, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781646221882" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Broughtupsy</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Catapult, January 23</strong></h5>
<p>I’ve been looking forward to this since I heard Cooke read the opening pages nearly two years ago. Set in the 1990s in Jamaica, this assured debut begins when Akúa’s brother dies and she leaves Canada to return to her native Jamaica in the hopes of reconnecting with her sister, Tamika. But when Akúa starts spending her time with a stripper, the difficult realities of being gay in a religious family and in a homophobic society provoke a reckoning for Akúa and Tamika. <em>–DB</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231335" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71rnxotamal-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71RNxOtamaL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1016,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Adam Shatz, The Rebel&#8217;s Clinic" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71RNxOtamaL._SL1500_-203x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71RNxOtamaL._SL1500_-694x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231335" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71RNxOtamaL._SL1500_-203x300.jpg" alt="Adam Shatz, The Rebel's Clinic" width="203" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71RNxOtamaL._SL1500_-203x300.jpg 203w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71RNxOtamaL._SL1500_-694x1024.jpg 694w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71RNxOtamaL._SL1500_-768x1134.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71RNxOtamaL._SL1500_-41x60.jpg 41w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71RNxOtamaL._SL1500_-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71RNxOtamaL._SL1500_.jpg 1016w" sizes="(max-width: 203px) 100vw, 203px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Adam Shatz, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374176426" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Rebel&#8217;s Clinic: The Revolutionary Lives of Frantz Fanon</a><br />
</em>FSG, January 23</strong></h5>
<p>In 2023, with Verso, Adam Shatz published <em>Writers and Missionaries: Essays on the Radical Imagination,</em> which looked at the sometimes thorny relationship between contemporary writers&#8217; writing and their politics, so a biography of Frantz Fanon makes sense as the subject of his new book. <em>The Rebel&#8217;s Clinic</em> charts the life of Fanon, who left Martinique to fight for France in WW2, then found himself drawn into Existentialism in the postwar years. An examination of one of the pre-eminent writers <em>and </em>activists of the postcolonial period, <em>The Rebel&#8217;s Clinic</em> also serves as a primer for Fanon&#8217;s most famous works, <em>Black Skin, White Masks </em>and <em>The Wretched of the Earth. –Samuel Rutter, contributing editor</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231336" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/912oumltlul-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/912oUMLTLuL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="994,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Kiley Reid, Come and Get It" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/912oUMLTLuL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/912oUMLTLuL._SL1500_-679x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231336" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/912oUMLTLuL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" alt="Kiley Reid, Come and Get It " width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/912oUMLTLuL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/912oUMLTLuL._SL1500_-679x1024.jpg 679w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/912oUMLTLuL._SL1500_-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/912oUMLTLuL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/912oUMLTLuL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/912oUMLTLuL._SL1500_.jpg 994w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Kiley Reid, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593328200" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Come and Get It</em></a><br />
Putnam, January 30</strong></h5>
<p>As a massive <em>Such a Fun Age </em>fan, I’ve been waiting for the new Kiley Reid for a long time. I thought her 2020 novel was so incisive and accessible, plotty and smart, that it makes me all the more excited for her next venture. Reid was good at every part of that story: depicting whiteness, the bond between babysitter and child, being 25 and lost, she could do it all, and did it all with warmth and empathy, even for the characters who didn’t always deserve it. This new book promises all the same ability at depth and poignancy through a fun, plotty story: a campus novel this time, about an RA named Millie, and her entanglement with a visiting professor. It’s a perfect recipe for a great January read: in a college setting, about discretion and desire, about money, want, and, most importantly, it’s by Kiley Reid. –<em>JH</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231337" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71bidlfcvpl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BIdLFcvpL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Chris Dixon, Read Write Own: Building the Next Era of the Internet" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BIdLFcvpL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BIdLFcvpL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231337" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BIdLFcvpL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" alt="Chris Dixon, Read Write Own: Building the Next Era of the Internet " width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BIdLFcvpL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BIdLFcvpL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BIdLFcvpL._SL1500_-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BIdLFcvpL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BIdLFcvpL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71BIdLFcvpL._SL1500_.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Chris Dixon, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593731383" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Read Write Own: Building the Next Era of the Internet</em></a><br />
Random House, January 30</strong></h5>
<p>One of the curious things about the internet is that discourse about the internet is often led by the same VCs and tech visionaries looking to capitalize on it, as evidenced by the rupture around EA in 2023. <em>Read Write Own</em> promises to put the eras of internet in context up to web3, and is blurbed by Bob Iger, Sam Altman, Mark Cuban (“Shark Tank; Dallas Mavericks”) and the president of Coinbase. –<em>JM</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231338" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/a1srrpayl6l-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1Srrpayl6L._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1044,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Gregory Pardlo, Spectral Evidence" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1Srrpayl6L._SL1500_-209x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1Srrpayl6L._SL1500_-713x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231338" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1Srrpayl6L._SL1500_-209x300.jpg" alt="Gregory Pardlo, Spectral Evidence " width="209" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1Srrpayl6L._SL1500_-209x300.jpg 209w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1Srrpayl6L._SL1500_-713x1024.jpg 713w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1Srrpayl6L._SL1500_-768x1103.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1Srrpayl6L._SL1500_-42x60.jpg 42w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1Srrpayl6L._SL1500_-35x50.jpg 35w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1Srrpayl6L._SL1500_.jpg 1044w" sizes="(max-width: 209px) 100vw, 209px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Gregory Pardlo, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781524731786" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Spectral Evidence</em></a><br />
Knopf, January 30</strong></h5>
<p>When one of America’s foremost poets publishes a collection for the first time in nearly a decade it is a major event—particularly when that poet is uniquely suited to grappling with what’s been going on in America over the past nine years&#8230; <i>Spectral Evidence</i> is Gregory Pardlo’s first collection of poetry since he won the Pulitzer Prize in 2015, and it picks up where <i>Digest</i> left off. As ever Pardlo moves through poetic registers with ease, from high to low and back again, as he witnesses the world in all its terrible beauty. From fallen heroes of professional wrestling (seriously) to this country’s infinite hostility to its Black citizens, Pardlo’s is the poetic eye (and heart) we need right now. –<em>Jonny Diamond, editor in chief</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231339" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71vioekwhxl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71viOeKwHXL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Ijeoma Oluo, Be a Revolution" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71viOeKwHXL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71viOeKwHXL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231339" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71viOeKwHXL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" alt="Ijeoma Oluo, Be a Revolution " width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71viOeKwHXL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71viOeKwHXL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71viOeKwHXL._SL1500_-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71viOeKwHXL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71viOeKwHXL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71viOeKwHXL._SL1500_.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Ijeoma Oluo, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063140189" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Be a Revolution</em></a><br />
Harper One, January 30</strong></h5>
<p>Ijeoma Oluo’s breakout hit <em>So You Want To Talk About Race</em> came out in 2018 but was discovered by many readers as the 2020 murder of George Floyd galvanized people across the U.S. to face the racist undercurrents. <em>Be a Revolution</em> sets out to look at how everyday people are using anti-racist approaches to reform systems big and small–in schools, in hospitals, in criminal justice–and map a way forward for those who want to push for change. –<em>JM</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="231340" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/91byndg2u-l-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91ByNDG2u-L._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="967,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Kwame Alexander, ed., This Is the Honey: An Anthology of Contemporary Black Poets" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91ByNDG2u-L._SL1500_-193x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91ByNDG2u-L._SL1500_-660x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-231340" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91ByNDG2u-L._SL1500_-193x300.jpg" alt="Kwame Alexander, ed., This Is the Honey: An Anthology of Contemporary Black Poets " width="193" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91ByNDG2u-L._SL1500_-193x300.jpg 193w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91ByNDG2u-L._SL1500_-660x1024.jpg 660w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91ByNDG2u-L._SL1500_-768x1191.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91ByNDG2u-L._SL1500_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91ByNDG2u-L._SL1500_-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91ByNDG2u-L._SL1500_.jpg 967w" sizes="(max-width: 193px) 100vw, 193px" /></p>
<h5><strong>Kwame Alexander, ed., <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780316417525" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>This Is the Honey: An Anthology of Contemporary Black Poets</em></a><br />
Little, Brown, January 30</strong></h5>
<p>This collection of “resilient joy” includes work from Rita Dove, Jericho Brown, Ross Gay, Tracy K. Smith and Terrance Hayes that captures poignant moments of beauty and pride: Jacqueline A.Trimble likens “Black woman joy” to indigo, tassels, foxes, and peacock plumes. Tyree Daye, Nate Marshall, and Elizabeth Acevedo reflect on the meaning of “home” through food, from Cuban rice and beans to fried chicken gizzards. I feel this will make a good gift in 2024. –<em>JM</em></p>
										
										<div class="content-page-links"><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/2/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num prev-link"></span></a><span class="page-link-numbers"> <span class="post-page-numbers current" aria-current="page"><span class="page-link-num">1</span></span> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/2/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">2</span></a> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/3/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">3</span></a> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/4/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">4</span></a> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/5/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">5</span></a> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/6/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">6</span></a> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/7/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">7</span></a></span> <a href="?single=true">Full Page</a><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/2/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num next-link">&gt;&gt;</span></a></div>										
																		
